{
  "text": "The Imperial College surgical assessment device (ICSAD) is another method of assessing surgical skills that utilize hand motion analysis. Sensors are placed on the dorsal surface of the trainee's hands while they perform a task and the hand motion is tracked. Their movement is translated into a computerized tracing of hand motion by the sensors. This provides an index of technical skill in both laparoscopic and open procedures that has been shown to have good concordance with OSATS scores [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Although the ICSAD has shown to be a valid indicator of operative skill, the evaluation metrics that are produced do not provide the trainee with feedback that can be used effectively for educational purposes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "12306540",
    "[CITATION_2]": "196362007",
    "[CITATION_3]": "15358806",
